## FAQ

### Q1: How many hours per week should a first-year student study?
A standard guideline is **2–3 hours of study time per credit hour** per week. For a 15-credit semester, that equals 30–45 hours of study outside of class, plus 15 hours in class, totaling 45–60 hours per week. Students who study fewer than 20 hours per week outside class are significantly more likely to earn a GPA below 2.0 in their first semester (University of Texas at Austin, 2023).

### Q2: What is the best way to take notes in a college lecture?
The **Cornell Note-Taking System** is widely recommended: divide your page into a cue column (left) and notes column (right), then summarize at the bottom. Handwritten notes, or typed notes that rephrase concepts rather than transcribe verbatim, improve retention by **30–40%** compared to verbatim typing (Psychological Science, 2014).

### Q3: When should I start studying for final exams?
Begin reviewing for finals at least **three weeks before exam week**. Create a study schedule that allocates more time to courses with higher credit weight or lower current grades. Cramming in the final 48 hours is associated with average exam scores **12–15% lower** than students who spread review over three weeks (Review of Educational Research, 2014).

